Losing Chester was definitely not great for Linkin Park, but Emily has proven she has what it takes to really bring new life to the band. It 's clear she isn 't trying to be the new Chester, because she knows that just cannot be done at all. Instead she brings a completely different and new experience to the band, that I think works way better than I could have ever imagined. This sound, this absolutely incredible sound, I could feel in my chest, and it felt extraurdinary. There was so much power here that you can hear from beginning to end.  I 'm excited to see what 's next to come for the new Linkin Park. I 'm sure there is much more incredible stuff that they 're gonna bring to the table, and that Emily is gonna be along for the ride. Keep it up you guys!

I 've listened to Linkin Park from around my 13/14 years old to my 16 years old, it helped me through college that was honestly an horrible period for me. Chester was already gone when I started to listen to Linkin Park, but I think I 've possibly seen all the interviews of him that exists on this earth, all the bloopers, funny videos of him and all. At this time I saw him a bit like an older brother that helps you and gives you advices. I cried MANY times thinking about his death, I really grieved his loss even though I didn 't already like him when he died. But he was so human, so kind, it 's not one those celebrities that are kind for their appearance and reputation. You could see he really was someone deeply kind. When I heard Emily for the first time I was angry, feeling like they 've tried to replace Chester. It was like 3 weeks ago. Today I listened again and I cried. It 's been 4 years I don 't listen to Linkin Park anymore but actually I realize that I still miss Chester. I cried because I 'm proud that his friends got up again and continued their passion and their friendship. Haters are stupid because we all know (normal people) that Chester would have been so proud of them as he dealt with pain too. Thanks for that Linkin Park members, Emily too. It 's an honor, not a replacement. I hope people will understand.

I actually don 't  remember anyone asking for this, to dig up the legacy of a band from its grave because its missing one of its core members. you know the people who asked for this? greedy record execs.  This is like the Jackson 5 calling themselves the jackson 5 and replacing michael with janet, no, latoya.  This is like Nirvana not renaming themselves Foo fighters  after  Kurt 's passing   What this  IS Like is the shameless motown acts trying to replace dying members because they didn 't manage their money correctly during their hay day so they have to tour as a shadow of themselves.   REVIVING Linkin Park, is fine... AS SOMETHING ELSE not named Linkin Park. You could have even named  the new band after an old song or album so it is still tied to the original band, but you simply replace the front man  and call it the same thing, Then adding the political dynamic of it being a woman  is just vile and reeks of trying to farm some ESG score instead of doing this out of love.   You COULD have even gotten away with it by using an AI version of Chester on songs that were unfinished, unreleased that CLEARLY sounded like they were written while he was alive or had him in mind ( like This one). Instead this comes across as trying to Mandela Effect him out of all the old songs that put the band on the map.   Emily should have been used only for new songs and not on any  'nostalgia  ' tracks(Like This one) . I 'm tired of corporate sh*tbags using nostalgia as a weapon because they  DON 'T KNOW  how to find anyone making something new that 's worth while. Everything since 2015 as been  Remastered,   genderswap,  gay swap, Rebooted.... WHERE THE  F**K IS NEW AND ORIGINAL ?

This to me isn 't Linking Park anymore. Linking Park was Chester, period. Even when he was alive they wanted to replace him for a female singer and he was devastated with it.  Yeah, her voice is great, but to me, LP died with Chester, this is just a cheap copy.  I would have respected them more if they created a  'new ' band, like many other bands did when the core member passed away. I would probably even buy their stuff, but, not like this. If they did  'Linkin Park feat Emily ' I would have no problem with that. Like this it seems like they are either to cash out on the fame that they got, because of Chester 's vocals, or trying to erase his legacy. What set LP apart, to me, was Chester 's voice! Without it, it 's just noise and yet another mediocre band going around.  Emily deserves fame, absolutely, but because of her talent and not because she 's attached to LP. She deserves her own band, not what remains of a once amazing band.

The song is very good, we can certainly feel that Shinoda 's touch.  Thumbs up if you agree with the following: The thing is: they should change the Linkin Park name. In every other band when such a leader dies, even if they want to keep doing music they move to newer projects. Would you imagine a Metallica without James Hatfield ? Would you imagine an Avenged Sevenfold without M. Shadows ? ACDC without Angus Young now that Malcolm passed away ?  Impossible right ?  It 's the same here. Nothing wrong about the song or album 's quality and nothing wrong about continuing in making music together guys, but you should baptise the band with a different name. Well back to Linkin Park roots. We need a Linkin Park album like this right now. Chester Bennington was legendary in the same way all of the OG Linkin Park members are to this band, but Emily Armstrong is an incredible choice to carry the torch and her voice sits well within their mix. The best way I can describe these full body goosebumps im feeling while I listen to this' I 'd never thought i 'd feel those from Linkin Park again after that day' and im happy to be proven wrong. Chester to me is a somber yet peaceful area in my mind despite the surrounding chaos, a place I lived in for years as a youth and he helped me make it a place to recover mentally from the world. A place where we could discover ourselves, to gain and find new strength to then be able to face whatever opposed us. When he passed It may sound silly but I started to question everything about my existence and despite tears welling up just thinking about it' it still feels like he is with us, a part of us, and because of his strength to carry our burdens and teaching us to stand against, we have to carry on that legacy. At the end with the synth it feels like a sunset with the ghostly outline of the flag bearer from hybrid theory in the dusty landscape from the In the End  video and the horizon is blank just like this new canvas for LP. No one can replace Chester' but we can keep his spirit alive of saying no. Saying I wont take this. Screaming from your soul at the pain and heartache of even just existing sometimes, and I wish you luck LP ❤ Thank you for making this and now we got the 15+ second scream we 've waited years to hear again' As a drummer I feel like once Colin stretches his legs some more I feel like you guys are on the way to something good and please continue ❤

Great song.  Before we get into some thoughts I 'm having, let me be clear: Emily is doing a great job, and I am excited to see how things proceed for Linkin Park from here onwards.  That out of the way. I heard an audible gasp for air at the end of the long scream... so on a second listen I 've confirmed that there are at least 4 such sounds in this recording. Given circumstances, comparisons are inevitable... so: Chester 's breathing tends to be less obtrusive, not perfect by any means, for example there 's a nasty gasp in  'New Divide ' and that 's just off the top of my head, but I am unaware of a song with him with this many gasps this loud (there are two small ones in  'Given Up ').  Now... is this Emily 's fault? Maybe, but it could also be the recording studio or editing.  I am not exhaustively familiar with especially the newer albums so maybe One More Light is even worse, and it would demonstrably not be Emily.  Then regarding the recent Live performances with Emily, I caught two cases where she steals a breath in a line that Chester sang on one breath (one in  'Numb ' and one in  'What I 've Done '' also a fair bit of gasping in the  'What I 've Done ' I 'm chalking it up to being tired towards the end of the show).  I doubt many singers could match the force of nature that was Chester Bennington, and even fewer could do so while singing in this sort of style, so this would certainly not be a disqualifying failure on Emily 's part, but I do think it shows room for improvement, either for her personally or for the band as a whole. This has also given me a new level of appreciation for Chester.  I am eager to see the future of Linkin Park.

I’m so happy about this to be honest, cause I gave her unconditional support since day one, as I could feel the right energy in her performances to fit the group. The album will be a massive release and the tour will be too. And what I love about this return to scenes is that, at least so far, they demonstrated that it is not about money, but it is about doing music and performing.  I have very high hopes about the album, but after many years I’d be probably already satisfied with these two singles.   Not that I didn’t appreciate the last albums, but my LP flame took fire with the first albums, and the late switch to pop never really convinced me. The Hunting Party was such a complicated album to listen by being 17, that I started to appreciate it just now. And the rest were another thing.  This to say that the guys I really don’t think they will tour for money, but primarily to satisfy their need for having a stage as a way to let out all of what they have inside, would it be accumulated or recent.  Long life to LP

Heavy is the Crown  Heavy is the Crown = 왕관의 무게 조금이라도 부진할때마다 수많은 악플을 받는 페이커는 왕관의 무게를 지금까지 견디고있고 레전드 보컬 체스터 베닝턴의 자리를 대체하려는 새 보컬 에밀리도 무거운 왕관의 무게를 견뎌야함  심지어 체스터베닝턴의 상징이던 스크리밍창법을 에밀리가 그대로 따라하고있음. 비교를 피하지 않고 왕관의 무게를 견디려는 모습  게다가 밴드의 중심인 보컬 = 롤의 중심인 미드  린킨파크를 알고 T1을 알면 이 서사에 공감할거임

Thank you, Emily, for being a part of this amazing band that I grew up with! Thank you, Linkin Park! Please never stop doing what you love! I am right there with you guys wherever this journey will lead us! I will carry Chester with me in my heart for the rest of my life and I would love for this band to go on for at least one day more than eternity!  Emily, please keep going on, no matter what the world may say. I don 't want to use the word  'fan ' so true friends of this band will agree that we 'll be there with you always. I started listening to Linkin Park from animated music videos (AMVs) based on Naruto a long time ago. I felt happy and sad with this band, I grieved with it and now I get to see this band start from zero...I am grateful to everyone involved in their success and especially I am grateful to Linkin Park for being a part of my life.

I didn’t believe Chester, cause he was my childhood and my teenage, but after 7 years and after coming back with two singles having this magnitude, I can’t see LP without Emily to be honest.  I’ve loved my whole life Evanescence too, so I am just so happy she became the vocalist of my favourite band ever.  Respect till the last breath to Chester, but we all should acknowledge that they decided to go on with the project, even if with a different configuration.  I’m happy for them to be honest, just imagine how difficult the moment itself could have been, and how long it took to recover from it. And the bravery to come back in this way. Just wow.

I 'm blown away by the new songs with Emily so far. I can hear elements of every previous album with a layer of something new preventing it from being a stale rehash of older music.  Emptiness Machine had echoes of A Thousand Suns ' Burning in the Skies, Minutes to Midnight 's What I 've Done, Hunting Party 's Final Masquerade with shades of New Divide thrown in. Heavy is the Crown reminds me of Meteora 's Faint, Minutes to Midnight 's Bleed It Out, and Hunting Party 's Guilty all the Same.  Given how different those albums were from each other it 's impressive that they can incorporate those styles without making an incoherent mess, and on top of that they still manage to keep it sounding fresh. I 'm super hyped for the album release if these two tracks are any indication of what we can expect.

Actually it would be stupid not to see that the songs being released not only musically give back a proper LP feeling, but also lyrics aren’t casual at all, and rightfully they push on the need for acceptance that for sure Emily feels.  Emptiness Machine:  “Let you cut me open  Just to watch me bleed (the haters?) Gave up who I am for who you wanted me to be (fans want Chester and not her, who tries to be accepted) Don’t know why I’m hoping For what I won’t receive (!!!) Falling for the promise of the emptiness machine (I interpret it as the society btw more than the fanbase, but it’s a personal interpretation) […] I only wanted to be part of something (she arrived there with them just to play jams, and slowly she became part of the group, but she still feels having to justify herself for taking the spot)”  And indeed, on the next song she speaks of a crown, clearly the one of Chester, being heavy.  There are for sure other meanings, and indeed good songs are allegories who can feel the most related to them even when stories are very different. But I still feel there’s a lot of Emily fear of inappropriateness in all of this. However I’m happy she’s destroying every stage so far!

Yeah we can definitely say that in comparison to One More Light (which I think is a great album by the way and I 'm saying that as someone who doesn 't really listen to pop that much, I 'm not trying to slate it when I say this), From Zero is already shaping up to be back along the lines of the Linkin Park everyone fell in love with back in the day and I 'm here for it. I thought Emily sounded great when they did this live the other night and she sounds great here too, the haters can say what they want about her vocals and that 's fine but I think she 's slotting in pretty nicely so far, obviously she 's not Chester nor is she trying to be even with that long scream but she 's doing her own thing and I 'm vibing with it. As far as Chester 's mom and son are concerned, I think they just need help (especially his son as he cut off contact with his dad not long before he died from what I understand and in my opinion is glamourizing this whole thing) because evidently they still haven 't quite gotten over his death yet and that 's perfectly understandable but despite being his family, they have no right to try and use his name against the rest of the band like was his band and his alone and assume all the songs were only his just because he sang the majority of them like I think they 're trying to do when they have no legal right or say in any sense over this reunion and anybody with common sense knows that a band is about everybody 's collective effort, no band revolves around one singular person no matter how big some personalities or iconic some voices may be. His mother even said he told her Mike belittled him, which I think is complete and utter bullshit on her part designed to further the division because not long after he joined, Chester quite literally helped Mike keep his spot in the band early on because the label wanted to either demote or simply get rid of him to focus solely on Chester and he wouldn 't let them do it plus Mike has never struck me as the type of guy that would repay that kindness in such a cruel way especially from what I 've read of personal experiences the fans have had with him, we 'd have probably known about it by now if it was true because Chester was always really open in his interviews up until the end. They can be upset about it all they want as can the haters but how about they don 't try to ruin it for the fans who are enjoying this new era of Linkin Park such as myself, we 're all allowed to have our own opinions and we won 't agree on everything but let 's separate art from the people and just be glad they 're back

Emily Armstrong cannot adequately replace Chester Bennington, as her vocal delivery exhibits a completely different tonal quality. While Bennington mesmerized listeners with his unmistakable melancholy and profound emotional depth, Armstrong lacks the ability to elicit the same level of emotional resonance. Chester, with his almost elegiac and vulnerable voice, skillfully created a cathartic experience through his melodies—something entirely missing in Armstrong 's grittier and more clipped vocal approach.  Armstrong’s voice, though undeniably powerful, lacks the subtlety and the melancholic anguish that were hallmarks of Chester’s style. Furthermore, her performances lack the expansiveness and lasting impact that Chester 's vocals had, along with the absence of those memorable, sing-along choruses that leave a lasting impression. This diminishes her suitability as a replacement in such an emotionally charged musical environment.  Some may argue,  'Emily isn 't supposed to replace Chester, ' but that argument clearly doesn’t hold up. When stepping into a band so deeply defined by the emotional gravitas of Chester 's voice, any new vocalist will inevitably face direct comparisons. The void left by Chester demands someone who can preserve, or at least reflect, that same depth of feeling. Whether intended or not, the expectation exists. Armstrong’s inability to replicate or channel that core experience makes it clear that, in practice, she is expected to fill a role Chester uniquely embodied. Without doing so, she falls short, which is why this argument fails to justify her place in comparison to Chester.

I discovered Linkin Park in a unusual way: from an online review written of the album Reroute to Remain by In Flames (of which I 'm a fan by chance), in which the person who wrote review make compared the album 's sound with Linkin Park. I thought the band 's name was so cool that I decided to try listening to see if the two bands were really similar. I was disappointed, because in my opinion they are not the same at all, but I really liked the variety of musical styles Linkin Park 's albums presented and, of course, the voice of the incredible Chester (R.I.P). So this will be the band 's first release since I became a fan of them. I liked what I heard from The Emptiness Machine, but this new one is also great. May it be Emily Armtrong 's first of many albums with the band 🤘🤘🤘
